  "tacticalAnalysis": {
    "ENG": {
      "summary": "England controlled this match from the first whistle in a 4-2-3-1 shape, dominating xG 3.33 vs 0.82. KANE's brace either side of half-time was the platform, with BELLINGHAM adding a third seconds into the second half. Croatia's brief period of parity (1-1 and 2-2) was undone by England's relentless pressing — 262 total pressures — and clinical finishing from four different goal involvements across the squad.",
      "strengths": [
        "KANE outstanding — brace (11' pen, 41' header), 7 shots, 11.5 km covered. Worked Croatia's high defensive line brilliantly and led the press with 42 indirect pressures",
        "BELLINGHAM's early second-half goal at 46' was decisive — his ability to arrive late into the box from AM position and convert a low pass showed Croatia couldn't handle England's movement",
        "ANDERSON ran most km (12 km), made most tackles (6/3 won) and most direct pressures (12) — the engine that kept Croatia at bay during their spells of pressure",
        "Four different scorers across the squad (KANE x2, BELLINGHAM, RASHFORD) showed collective threat — Croatia had no individual to mark out of the game"
      ],
      "weaknesses": [
        "Despite xG dominance, England conceded twice — BATURINA's 35' equaliser came from a passing error and MUSA's 49' goal showed defensive concentration lapses right after going 3-1 up",
        "Pass completion only 87% and KANE's 70% pass accuracy suggest England were not always comfortable on the ball under Croatia's high press (295 pressures, most direct in the match)",
        "Conceded 85 line breaks — Croatia's wing-backs STANISIC and PERISIC caused constant problems down the flanks despite the final scoreline",
        "BELLINGHAM subbed at 80' with England 3-2 up rather than protecting the lead — a calculated risk that worked but showed Tuchel's aggressive game-management style"
      ]
    },
    "CRO": {
      "summary": "Croatia lost 2-4 but gave England a genuine test, twice equalising before ultimately being undone by England's quality. Their 3-4-3 system with MODRIC orchestrating generated 85 line breaks — more than England — and LIVAKOVIC's 7 saves kept them in contention. A lack of clinical edge (0.82 xG from 10 shots) and second-half fatigue after intense pressing (295 total) ultimately cost them.",
      "strengths": [
        "LIVAKOVIC world-class in goal — 7 saves from 11 on-target shots (64% save%). Without his intervention in the 55th-minute triple save sequence, England would have gone 4-1 at that point",
